# Zig Conventions

Target: Zig 0.16 (current stable). Systems programming, CLIs, embedded. Pre-1.0, breaks across releases — pin `minimum_zig_version` in `build.zig.zon`. Tiger Style is native here (TigerBeetle).

## Memory & Allocators

- No hidden allocations. Every allocating function takes an `std.mem.Allocator` explicitly — no global/default allocator.
- Pair each allocation with `defer`/`errdefer` in the same scope. Arena (`ArenaAllocator`) for batch/scoped lifetimes.
- Tests use `std.testing.allocator` (fails on leak); `std.heap.DebugAllocator` (formerly `GeneralPurposeAllocator`) in debug catches leaks/use-after-free.
- Slices (`[]T`, bounds-checked) over many-item pointers; `[]const T` for read-only views.

## Errors

- Errors are values: error unions (`!T`), explicit error sets, propagate with `try`, clean up with `errdefer`.
- Handle or propagate every error; no `catch unreachable` unless provably impossible (then assert).
- No `unreachable` or `.?` on input-derived values — only where an invariant guarantees presence.

## Language & Idioms

- `comptime` for generics/compile-time work instead of macros or runtime reflection.
- Closed alternatives as a tagged union (`union(enum)`); `switch` exhaustively, no `else` when the compiler should flag new unhandled variants.
- Optionals (`?T`) unwrapped with `orelse` / `if (x) |v|`, never a blind `.?`.
- No hidden control flow: no operator overloading, no exceptions, no lossy implicit conversions. Visible casts (`@intCast`, `@truncate`).
- `+`/`-`/`*` are checked in safe builds — use `+%` (wrapping) / `+|` (saturating) only when that's the intent.
- `defer`/`errdefer` for all cleanup, next to the acquisition.

## Build & Test

- `zig build` (steps in `build.zig`, deps in `build.zig.zon`); `zig fmt` is the canonical formatter — keep it in CI.
- Ship `Debug`/`ReleaseSafe` where safety matters; `ReleaseFast`/`ReleaseSmall` only when measured and justified.
- `test "..."` blocks colocated; `std.testing.allocator` so leaks fail; `expectError` for error paths.

## Naming & Structure

- `TitleCase` for types (and functions returning a type), `camelCase` for functions, `snake_case` for variables/fields.
- Files named for their primary type, else `snake_case`. No `util`/`common`/`helpers` grab-bags — name by what it provides.

## Tiger Style

- Assert preconditions/postconditions/invariants with `std.debug.assert`; assert on both sides of a boundary.
- Loops over external input have explicit bounds; no unbounded recursion. Named constants for limits/sizes — no magic numbers.
